The Arroyo is a dry canyon in the eastern desert, carved by a branch of the Iseth watershed that no longer flows. It connects to the Deepwell Confluence basin. Seasonal floodwater once ran through it; drought cycles killed the river permanently.
The canyon was repurposed from flood channel to toll corridor. Water volume was converted into legal obligation. Travelers were assessed, oaths recorded against thirst, debts written against drought.
Five historical layers remain active simultaneously. Keeper-era: thirst oaths, silt tallies, witness stones recording distance and water debt. Salt Ledger: toll courts in cutbanks, confiscation vaults, mortuary intake for debtors who died in arrears ("unpaid names" with rites withheld). Pyramid: Moon-descending legal language reframing debt default as spiritual trespass, creating palimpsest inscriptions. Synod: simplified toll liturgy where "authorized thirst" served as both prayer and threat. Ecological: scorpion colonies nesting through ossuary chambers, chitin and resin embedding in record halls.
Four factions contest the canyon. Charter Reclaimers: synod-descended militants running extortion checkpoints with copied charter rods. Dustbound Court-Dead: undead former assessors demanding declarations, escorting intruders to judgment points. Brood of the Resin Matriarch: canyon-adapted mega-scorpions centered in warm seep zones. Fault Manifestations: dust vortices with voice-like harmonics, ash figures, magnetic grit storms aligned to old survey marks.
Canyon walls are covered in overwritten inscriptions, each regime carving atop the last. No modern faction understands all layers, but all claim legitimacy from them.

