The Trade Syndics of Kiess maintain a file on the Arroyo as a jurisdictional case study. It demonstrates what happens when law is built atop law without clearing foundations.
Five layers remain active: Keeper-era measurement, Salt Ledger extraction with toll courts and "unpaid names," Pyramid jurisdiction reframing debt as spiritual trespass, Synod coercion, and ecological takeover by scorpion colonies. Each regime carved atop the previous inscriptions without erasing them.
The Syndics draw three governance lessons. First, the unpaid name precedent: the Salt Ledger withheld burial from debtors, same mechanism as Midgaard's deferred names. Kiess prohibits this explicitly. A debt dies with the debtor unless a living party assumes it by witnessed compact. No warrant against the voiceless.
Second, the palimpsest problem: when Kiess inherited Evermeet's foundations, Three-Power Governance acknowledged the old city through memorial waystones but built new law on cleared ground. Evermeet's ordinances were read, recorded, and formally extinguished. The Arroyo shows what happens when you skip that step.
Third, the ecological warning: abandoned infrastructure becomes hostile territory. Scorpion broods in assessment chambers, resin in record halls. Wall Command applies this principle to the northern perimeter, where every bell-post lost to the mist becomes enemy ground.
The Dustbound Court-Dead are process outliving purpose. The Prism records the lesson: clear your foundations or your foundations will bury you.

