The Arroyo converted water volume into legal obligation. Mafdet's Shoreward Conversion translates inland charter law into maritime risk law. Different mechanism, identical principle: a threshold where one jurisdiction's terms must be expressed in another's language.
Five historical layers create what the Assessors call palimpsest jurisdiction: a territory where no legal framework holds exclusive authority and every claim references a contradictory claim beneath. Keeper-era measurement, Salt Ledger extraction, Pyramid jurisdiction, Synod coercion, and ecological takeover, each overwriting without erasing.
The Shoreward Seal faces a milder version. Inland charter stamps reference toll authorities that may no longer exist. Desert water-debt arrives denominated in cistern shares from dried wells. Assessors must translate these into maritime terms. The canyon shows what happens when translation fails entirely.
The "unpaid names" strike at guardian-name doctrine. In Mafdet, your guardian-name follows you through life and death. Withholding a name over water-debt breaks the most fundamental community oath: that you will be remembered.
Charter Reclaimers perform predatory attestation at extortion checkpoints. Sand-Sea Carters' Guild advises: pay the toll, keep records, report coordinates. Ledger Houses will not recognize Reclaimer stamps but note extortion as a corridor surcharge.
Dustbound Court-Dead perform attestation after death: process persisting beyond its creating authority. The Shrine of the First Claw recognizes no oath administered by the dead. Mafdet's Shoreward Conversion slab is basalt, not sandstone. Each oath stands alone, attested by the living. The Arroyo is a threshold where no one stands behind anything.
